          <div class="learn__post__content">
            <p>
              Lets talk about why we at Metabase dont allow people to join
              data from multiple databases (and give you a few ideas and
              workarounds if you absolutely have to do this).
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/cross-db-joins/combining-data.png"
                alt="Combining data from different database"
              />
            </p>

            <h2 id="why-doesnt-metabase-do-cross-database-joins">
              Why doesnt Metabase do cross-database joins?
            </h2>

            <p>
              Metabase isnt a storage engine or a query engine. Metabase
              connects to your database, sends queries to the database; then the
              database itself executes the queries, and Metabase pulls the
              results and visualizes them. Your data stays in your database, and
              all the processing happens inside your database.
            </p>

            <p>
              Most databases are optimized to process queries on their own data
              efficiently, but they have no native way to communicate with other
              databases. To join data from two different databases, Metabase
              would need to pull data from multiple databases into its own
              memory or write it on disk, run the queries on that data. This <em
                >could</em
              > work for small tables, but it wouldnt scale well (not to mention
              the downside that Metabase would need to store your data <em
                >outside</em
              > of your database).
            </p>

            <p>
              Imagine hundreds of people running queries that require joins from
              several databases, each with a ton of rows, putting all that data
              into memory of your Metabase, and running unoptimized queries
              against that joined data. That would get very slow (and very
              expensive).
            </p>

            <p>
              Some other BI tools work around this problem by creating an
              intermediate layer between your database and BI to store data,
              which often means requiring large, complicated - and <em
                >pricey</em
              > - deployments.
            </p>

            <p>
              To keep Metabase light and simple, we havent built that
              functionality directly into our product (yet! Never say never 
              check in on the <a href="/roadmap">Metabase product roadmap</a> every
              now and then). But here are some ways you can set up your data to allow
              for queries involving multiple databases, while remaining performance-conscious
              and in control of your data.
            </p>

            <h2 id="best-solution-use-a-data-warehouse">
              Best solution: use a data warehouse
            </h2>

            <p>
              (<a
                href="/learn/grow-your-data-skills/data-landscape/data-mart-data-warehouse-data-lake"
                >Or a data lake</a
              >. Or a data lakehouse. The world is your oyster.)
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/cross-db-joins/data-warehouse.png"
                alt="Diagram of a data warehouse"
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              The gist is: you set up an <a
                href="/learn/grow-your-data-skills/data-landscape/etl-landscape"
                >ETL</a
              > (or ELT, or ELTL, you get the idea) process to regularly bring data
              from all the different databases and third-party systems that youre
              using, house that data it in a single place - a data warehouse - and
              use that data warehouse to support all your analytical needs.
            </p>

            <p>The upsides are:</p>

            <ul>
              <li>
                All the data is already in one place, you dont need to send
                data over the network to and from another database.
              </li>
              <li>
                The architecture of modern data warehouses is optimized for
                analytical queries.
              </li>
              <li>You are in full control of your data.</li>
            </ul>

            <p>
              Metabase can connect to all the most popular data warehouses like <a
                href="/data-sources/snowflake">Snowflake</a
              >, <a href="/data-sources/amazon-redshift">Redshift</a>, <a
                href="/data-sources/bigquery">BigQuery</a
              >, <a href="/data-sources/amazon-redshift">Databricks</a> and others.
              Check out <a
                href="/learn/grow-your-data-skills/data-landscape/which-data-warehouse"
                >Which data warehouse should I use?</a
              >.
            </p>

            <p>
              To build a data warehouse, youd need, at minimum, to set up the
              infrastructure, build a pipeline to copy the data, and model the
              data into shapes appropriate for analytics - a nontrivial upfront
              investment. But it creates a consistent, performant, and scalable
              environment to support your analytics, so it will pay off in the
              future.
            </p>

            <p>
              If you cant invest in building a data warehouse just yet, there
              are some alternatives:
            </p>

            <h2 id="combine-series-on-dashboard-cards">
              Combine series on dashboard cards
            </h2>

            <p>
              If all you need to do is to combine two series on a single chart,
              and each series is built on a data from a single database, you can
              add both series to a dashboard card.
            </p>

            <p>
              For example, say you want to show number of users by month, taken
              from your Users database, on the same charts and average payment
              amount by month from your Finance database together. All you need
              to do is add those series to a single dashboard cardno
              cross-database join needed.
            </p>

            <p>
              See our docs for <a
                href="/docs/latest/dashboards/multiple-series#combining-multiple-questions-on-one-dashboard-card"
                >combining saved questions</a
              >.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/cross-db-joins/combine-series.png"
                alt="Combine two series on a dashboard"
              />
            </p>

            <h2 id="postgresql-use-foreign-data-wrappers">
              PostgreSQL: use Foreign Data Wrappers
            </h2>

            <p>
              If you want to combine data from two Postgres databases (or a
              Postgres database and some other databases), and you dont want to
              build a data warehouse, you can use a <a
                href="https://wiki.postgresql.org/wiki/Foreign_data_wrappers"
                >Foreign Data Wrapper (FDW)</a
              >. Foreign Data Wrappers allow your Postgres database to read data
              from remote data stores, including other databases.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/cross-db-joins/fdw.png"
                alt="Diagram of a postgres foreign data wrappers"
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              To query one Postgres database from another you can use the <a
                href="https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/postgres-fdw.html"
                ><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >postgres_fdw</code
                > extension</a
              > thats part of the official PostgreSQL distribution.
            </p>

            <p>Lets assume we have:</p>

            <ol>
              <li>
                A database <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >db1</code
                > with table <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >table1</code
                > in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >public</code
                > schema,
              </li>
              <li>
                A database <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >db2</code
                > with table <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >table2</code
                > in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >public</code
                > schema
              </li>
            </ol>

            <p>
              and we want to query data from <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
              > and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >table2</code
              > together.
            </p>

            <p>
              Well mirror the tables from <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db2</code
              > into a schema in <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
              >, so itll be possible connect to <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
              > (for example, with Metabase) and run queries to access data from
              <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db2</code>.
            </p>

            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  In your database admin tool (not in Metabase), run this script
                  on <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >db1</code
                  >. Make sure to substitute your own names and passwords.
                </p>

                <div class="language-sql highlighter-rouge">
                  <div class="highlight">
                    <pre
                      class="highlight">&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class="c1"&gt;------ Run on DB1: ------&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- Add the postgres_fdw extension&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="k"&gt;CREATE&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;EXTENSION&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;postgres_fdw&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- Create a server object to represent the foreign database&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- Specify the connection information for DB2 in OPTIONS&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- In this script we're connecting to a database inside the same server and that's why we use 'localhost'&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="k"&gt;CREATE&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;SERVER&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;db2_server&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="k"&gt;FOREIGN&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;DATA&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;WRAPPER&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;postgres_fdw&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="k"&gt;OPTIONS&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="k"&gt;host&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="s1"&gt;'localhost'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;dbname&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="s1"&gt;'db2'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;);&lt;/span&gt;

 &lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- Create a user mapping for the foreign server&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- It maps the user accessing DB1 (for example, metabase_user) to a user accessing DB2 (your_db2_user)&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- The user in DB1 will use that role to access the remote DB2 server&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;span class="k"&gt;CREATE&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;USER&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;MAPPING&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;FOR&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;metabase_user&lt;/span&gt;
     &lt;span class="n"&gt;SERVER&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;db2_server&lt;/span&gt;
     &lt;span class="k"&gt;OPTIONS&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="k"&gt;user&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="s1"&gt;'your_db2_user'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;password&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="s1"&gt;'your_db2_password'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;);&lt;/span&gt;

 &lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- Import public.table2 from DB2 into public schema of DB1.&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- You can use other schemas or create a new schema specifically for the foreign tables&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;span class="n"&gt;IMPORT&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;FOREIGN&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;SCHEMA&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;public&lt;/span&gt;
     &lt;span class="k"&gt;LIMIT&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;TO&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;table2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
     &lt;span class="k"&gt;FROM&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;SERVER&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;db2_server&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;INTO&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;public&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;

 &lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- You should be able to query table2 from DB1 now&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;span class="k"&gt;SELECT&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;FROM&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;table2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;/code&gt;</pre>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <p>
                  If you run into any problems, take a look at <a
                    href="https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/postgres-fdw.html"
                    >the docs for postgres_fdw</a>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Connect Metabase to your PostgreSQL database <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
                  > (the one that you mirrored foreign tables <em>into</em>).
                </p>

                <p>
                  Once the connection is established, you should see the foreign
                  table <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >table2</code
                  > show up in <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
                  > (along with <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
                  >) in Browse data in the Metabase nav sidebar.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Now that you can query both <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
                  > and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >table2</code
                  > from a connection to <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
                  >, you should be able to create queries joining data from <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
                  > and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >table2</code
                  > using either the query builder or SQL.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>

            <p>
              There are other foreign data wrappers - for example a FDW to query
              Oracle ot MySQL databases from Postgres - available as third-party
              tools, but if you decide to use third-party FDW, check that
              theyre still being actively maintained. Check the <a
                href="https://wiki.postgresql.org/wiki/Foreign_data_wrappers"
                >list of foreign data wrappers on the PostgreSQL wiki</a
              >.
            </p>

            <h2 id="mysql-create-a-view">MySQL: create a view</h2>

            <p>
              MySQL provides a native way to query data from a different
              database on the same server using syntax like <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >database.schema.table.field</code
              >. But in Metabase, when you connect to one database (lets call
              it <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code>),
              Metabase wont know that another database <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db2</code
              > exists on the same server, so you wont be able to run queries on
              <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code> that
              reference <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >db2</code
              >.
            </p>

            <p>
              The workaround is to create a view mirroring data from <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db2</code
              > inside <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >db1</code
              >.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/cross-db-joins/mysql-view.png"
                alt='Diagram of a MySQL view used to "mirror" a table'
              />
            </p>

            <p>So lets say you have:</p>

            <ol>
              <li>
                A database <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >db1</code
                > with table <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >table1</code
                >,
              </li>
              <li>
                A database <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >db2</code
                > with table <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >table2</code
                >,
              </li>
            </ol>

            <p>
              and you want to join data from <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
              > and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >table2</code
              >.
            </p>

            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  In your database admin tool (not in Metabase), create a view
                  in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >db1</code
                  > that selects <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table2</code
                  > from <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >db2</code
                  >:
                </p>

                <div class="language-sql highlighter-rouge">
                  <div class="highlight">
                    <pre
                      class="highlight">&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class="c1"&gt;------ Run on DB1: ------&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- Create a view for db2.table2 inside db1.&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="k"&gt;CREATE&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;VIEW&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;table2&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;AS&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span class="k"&gt;SELECT&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;FROM&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;db2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;table2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/code&gt;</pre>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Connect Metabase to your MySQL database <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
                  > (the one where created a view).
                </p>

                <p>
                  Once the connection is established, you should see the view <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table2</code
                  > show up in <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
                  > (along with <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
                  >) in Browse data in metabase navigation sidebar.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Now that you can access both <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
                  > and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >table2</code
                  > from a connection to <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
                  >, you should be able to create queries joining data from <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
                  > and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >table2</code
                  > using either the query builder or SQL.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>

            <h2 id="snowflake-create-a-view">Snowflake: create a view</h2>

            <p>
              Just like MySQL, Snowflake provides a native way to query data
              from a different database using syntax like <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >database.schema.table</code
              >. But in Metabase, when you connect to one database (lets call
              it <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code>),
              Metabase wont know that another database <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db2</code
              > exists , so you wont be able to run queries on <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
              > that reference <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db2</code
              >.
            </p>

            <p>
              The workaround is to create a view mirroring data from <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db2</code
              > inside <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >db1</code
              >. So lets say you have:
            </p>

            <ol>
              <li>
                A database <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >db1</code
                > with table <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >table1</code
                > in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >public</code
                > schema,
              </li>
              <li>
                A database <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >db2</code
                > with table <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >table2</code
                > in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >public</code
                > schema,
              </li>
            </ol>

            <p>
              and you want to join data from <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
              > and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >table2</code
              >.
            </p>

            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  In your database admin tool (not in Metabase), create a view
                  in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >db1</code
                  > that selects <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table2</code
                  > from <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >db2</code
                  >:
                </p>

                <div class="language-sql highlighter-rouge">
                  <div class="highlight">
                    <pre
                      class="highlight">&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class="c1"&gt;------ Run on DB1: ------&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="c1"&gt;-- Create a view for db2.public.table2 inside db1.&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="k"&gt;CREATE&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;VIEW&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;table2&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;AS&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span class="k"&gt;SELECT&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;FROM&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;db2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="k"&gt;public&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;table2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/code&gt;</pre>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Connect Metabase to your Snowflake database <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
                  > (the one where created a view).
                </p>

                <p>
                  Once the connection is established, you should see the view <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table2</code
                  > show up in <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
                  > (along with <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
                  >) in Browse data in metabase navigation sidebar.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Now that you can access both <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
                  > and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >table2</code
                  > from a connection to <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
                  >, you should be able to create queries joining data from <code
                    class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">table1</code
                  > and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                    >table2</code
                  > using either the query builder or SQL.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>

            <h2 id="use-a-federated-query-engine">
              Use a federated query engine
            </h2>

            <p>
              The job of a federated query engine is to give you a single
              interface to query and analyze data from different data sources.
              You can connect your federated query engine to multiple databases,
              then connect your Metabase to the federated engine, and query all
              the data through it as if it was in a single database.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/cross-db-joins/federated-query-engine.png"
                alt="Diagram of a federated query engine"
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              Its not going to be as fast as a dedicated data warehouse,
              because data warehouses can store data more efficiently and
              optimize queries, but it can be a good intermediate solution.
            </p>

            <p>
              Metabase can connect to several popular federated query engines: <a
                href="/data-sources/presto">Presto</a
              >, <a href="/data-sources/starburst">Trino and Starburst</a>, and <a
                href="/data-sources/amazon-athena">Athena</a
              >.
            </p>

            <h2 id="check-your-database-functionality">
              Check your database functionality
            </h2>

            <p>
              If youre using a database other than PostgresSQL or MySQL, and
              you cant use a federated query engine or build a data warehouse,
              check with your specific database - it might already have the
              functionality you need to resolve your specific use case.
            </p>

            <p>
              The idea: if your database has a way to read data from other
              databases, then you can use that functionality to get data from <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db2</code
              > into <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >db1</code
              >, then connect your Metabase to <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db1</code
              >, and have the data from <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">db2</code
              > show up in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >db1</code
              > ready for querying (and joining).
            </p>

            <p>
              For example, <a
                href="https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/external-tables"
                >BigQuery external tables</a
              >, or <a
                href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/dg/federated-overview.html"
                >Redshift federated queries</a
              > might work for some use cases. <a
                href="https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/query-federation/"
                >Databricks</a
              > and <a href="https://clickhouse.com/docs/integrations/index"
                >ClickHouse</a
              > provide similar functionality as well.
            </p>

